ed people to use the evil side of power. This foreshadowed the ways in which people exercise agency in contemporary Africa, as well as the proliferation of magical fears and witchcraft anxieties in present-day Gabon. Overturning theories of colonial and postcolonial nativism, this book is essential reading for historians and anthropologists of witchcraft, power, value, and the body.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aImperialism in popular culturezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aMagicxSocial aspectszGabon. 0aWitchcraftxSocial aspectszGabon. 7aHISTORY / Africa / Central.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002666zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002666.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles